{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659777"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:14:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20899"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20899"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13774"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97408"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13774","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13774"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20899"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80019"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11801"},{"type":"tags","id":"12722"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33201"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33202"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97408","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97408"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EGenomic imprinting is an epigenetic phenomenon that affects gene expression in a parent-of-origin specific manner. This process results in functional differences between maternal and paternal alleles for certain genes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the process of genomic imprinting?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deletion of redundant alleles after fertilisation","Equal expression from both parental alleles","Mutation of genes during gametogenesis","Selective silencing of specific parental alleles","Random inactivation of either maternal or paternal alleles"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGenomic imprinting involves the \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective silencing of specific parental alleles\u003C/strong\u003E through epigenetic mechanisms. This process occurs during gametogenesis and results in monoallelic gene expression based on parent of origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeletion of redundant alleles after fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E - Imprinting silences genes through reversible epigenetic modifications rather than permanent deletion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual expression from both parental alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes normal biallelic expression, not imprinting which shows parent-specific expression\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMutation of genes during gametogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Imprinting involves epigenetic regulation without DNA sequence changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom inactivation of either maternal or paternal alleles\u003C/strong\u003E - Imprinting follows specific patterns for particular genes and is not random\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe main mechanism involves DNA methylation at CG nucleotides and histone modifications established during gametogenesis. These marks are maintained through cell division. Examples include Prader-Willi syndrome and Angelman syndrome, which involve the same chromosomal region but show different effects depending on parental origin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genomic imprinting is an epigenetic process that selectively inactivates either the maternal or paternal allele of certain genes.","Imprinting occurs in gametes pre-fertilisation and is transmitted stably to all somatic cells through mitosis.","DNA methylation at CG nucleotides is a primary mechanism of genomic imprinting, along with histone modifications."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5; page 178."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80019"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20899"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80019"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T17:48:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T17:48:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13774"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97408"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11801"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Single-gene disorders with nonclassic inheritance","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-13T19:15:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T19:15:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12722","links":{"self":"htt